<taxonomicName id="2268E5F1D5B2196E553E11F8816859A5" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ambrosiophilus</taxonomicName>
Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009: 21.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B6CA2BF13D287A8990804AB63DB9288" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type species">
<paragraph id="515B99EDFB11C7F2F0DA0D99565811D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D56E1ABCB9AB17E091AEEF0FB8AC0D88" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="67DC2EE0C3B522FA9A5470D71DE3B202" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Stereocaulaceae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xyleborus restrictus" order="Lecanorales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="restrictus">
<emphasis id="6696BBB49B45E60C18465C000BD9E3CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xyleborus restrictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schedl, 1939b; original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE9C155532E222042D8AF4F94ED0AC93" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CC45E50B5B9687CA2366B8DFCC272641" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="04BECA0704E10459E785714F8338D677" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
1.95-4.5 mm, stout to elongate (2.27-2.92
<normalizedToken id="E1ADF6633E8F0BCF226126058EAE7419" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide) with elytral apex rounded and entire. 
<taxonomicName id="3A5E99726FBFF9FF3913A0D38A0BEF65" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="251668F951556B53F7659D3ACB81B2AE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the pronotum anterior margin typically without a carina or serrations; pronotal disc punctate; declivity rounded and steep; antennal club flattened, types 3 or 4; scutellum flat, flush; mycangial tufts absent; protibiae obliquely triangular; and procoxae contiguous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="19AAAC41EBA27EF30DEE94C70F15895E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="DACA1CEFEE848604C5CE5EDCE8044D22" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1FAD0EB27711A49A92BC8CEEB455F3FB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="6BE24D6E7C40BB0DB2DFD7BB8E09CBAC" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiodmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiodmus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6DCD816A9A597796C0F50BF82D4DD318" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiodmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is distinguished by the pronotal disc and lateral areas punctate, never asperate, and lateral profile of pronotal and elytral discs flat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="980FCDFEEF5E23B38C0C6422895F447E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="similar genera">
<paragraph id="C25DF0F00FE51A452F4032AEDC3A79E2" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Similar genera.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="055D8CD22416C03BD52C5427FF056C7F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="037A06642C77F72F4245FB2FCFE51452" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiodmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiodmus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63DE5C61B1D084E578C56133DD5B2BBF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiodmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D50A6C608131AF02A9BD47F75792B45D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="05A22A6D13BC9B2BA53251FA4BFA62CB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F8B22FAB4BB41F60CB5DA7961B88F325" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Found in temperate and tropical Asia, two species are established in the United States (
<bibRefCitation id="94DF00BB3EDD368DE2A90427FC49F2B8" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.768.24697" author="Gomez, DF" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="19 - 68" refId="B175" refString="Gomez, DF, Rabaglia, RJ, Fairbanks, KEO, Hulcr, J, 2018a. North American Xyleborini north of Mexico: a review and key to genera and species (Coleoptera, Curculionidae, Scolytinae). ZooKeys 768: 19 - 68, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.768.24697" title="North American Xyleborini north of Mexico: a review and key to genera and species (Coleoptera, Curculionidae, Scolytinae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.768.24697" volume="768" year="2018 a">Gomez et al. 2018a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0563565BBF3AD18F1AD7FFBE1399B7F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="gallery system">
<paragraph id="B66DCB58111DDDBFA5917E7752DB75CD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Gallery system.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72EB82A201B1BCE676CEF5301C7986F4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="E7C8CFB4658AAC54F564F3616569235E" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiodmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiodmus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="15AAE7CA4119701EAA0822AC645A906A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiodmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E544E998F56A5A042F4BAA54EA11B54A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="B7BCDD1B258D941D5A944FCE2D00F62B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EACF04F492C6EE06B25CF7A74975EF9A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="699E9BCA2859CD1D84B16FD88B11F356" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Eichhoff" baseAuthorityYear="1876" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus atratus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atratus">
<emphasis id="2BF489E2FE88C0DEB67EBC76BC319FF8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiophilus atratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C068B5CC179CE02A96FB4625C6E1AB0C" genus="A." lsidName="A. subnepotulus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="subnepotulus">
<emphasis id="7ED1A11893E6093DFA61746DF7C9C9C0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. subnepotulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are believed to use the same basidiomycete as 
<taxonomicName id="A1774EF116173D3762344738BFD33539" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiodmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiodmus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ED1915B0F62A2704C746ED988CEFF174" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiodmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above) (
<bibRefCitation id="D068D694747DA4F928FCA55AB2AE0805" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funeco.2016.07.002" author="Kasson, MT" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="86 - 96" refId="B225" refString="Kasson, MT, Wickert, KL, Stauder, CM, Macias, AM, Berger, MC, Simmons, DR, Short, DPG, DeVallance, DB, Hulcr, J, 2016. Mutualism with aggressive wood-degrading Flavodon ambrosius (Polyporales) facilitates niche expansion and communal social structure in Ambrosiophilus ambrosia beetles. Fungal Ecology 23: 86 - 96, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funeco.2016.07.002" title="Mutualism with aggressive wood-degrading Flavodon ambrosius (Polyporales) facilitates niche expansion and communal social structure in Ambrosiophilus ambrosia beetles." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funeco.2016.07.002" volume="23" year="2016">Kasson et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="4A9EB33E002AD3708223F6BE017B2037" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2017.08.004" author="Li, Y" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="984 - 989" refId="B246" refString="Li, Y, Bateman, CC, Skelton, J, Jusino, MA, Nolen, ZJ, Simmons, DR, Hulcr, J, 2017. Wood decay fungus Flavodon ambrosius (Basidiomycota: Polyporales) is widely farmed by two genera of ambrosia beetles. Fungal Biology 121: 984 - 989, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2017.08.004" title="Wood decay fungus Flavodon ambrosius (Basidiomycota: Polyporales) is widely farmed by two genera of ambrosia beetles." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2017.08.004" volume="121" year="2017">Li et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). However, some species are mycocleptic (
<bibRefCitation id="DDD28BB95F911FDCEB6835B1D669E89E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01055.x" author="Hulcr, J" journalOrPublisher="Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="3205 - 3212" refId="B203" refString="Hulcr, J, Cognato, AI, 2010b. Repeated evolution of theft in fungus farming ambrosia beetles. Evolution 64: 3205 - 3212, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01055.x" title="Repeated evolution of theft in fungus farming ambrosia beetles." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01055.x" volume="64" year="2010 b">Hulcr and Cognato 2010b</bibRefCitation>
). The female starts its gallery close to galleries of other ambrosia beetles. The fungus established by the 
<normalizedToken id="3A61DEAC1669F9E654874E8BFA629F5F" originalValue="‘host’">'host'</normalizedToken>
species grows in the galleries of 
<taxonomicName id="553B6CA6614D89A15D6A1B2532AE8198" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2009" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ambrosiophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ambrosiophilus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D5F85257B71F02D4C12F06B96CC5D9F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ambrosiophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which consequently has no need to transport its own ambrosia fungus, and lacks mycangia (
<bibRefCitation id="D2892D3764DE4BB6CE9458DE5591BE0E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01055.x" author="Hulcr, J" journalOrPublisher="Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="3205 - 3212" refId="B203" refString="Hulcr, J, Cognato, AI, 2010b. Repeated evolution of theft in fungus farming ambrosia beetles. Evolution 64: 3205 - 3212, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01055.x" title="Repeated evolution of theft in fungus farming ambrosia beetles." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1558-5646.2010.01055.x" volume="64" year="2010 b">Hulcr and Cognato 2010b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F5DA19774F95C390C134AF8C3504764A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funeco.2016.07.002" author="Kasson, MT" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="86 - 96" refId="B225" refString="Kasson, MT, Wickert, KL, Stauder, CM, Macias, AM, Berger, MC, Simmons, DR, Short, DPG, DeVallance, DB, Hulcr, J, 2016. Mutualism with aggressive wood-degrading Flavodon ambrosius (Polyporales) facilitates niche expansion and communal social structure in Ambrosiophilus ambrosia beetles. Fungal Ecology 23: 86 - 96, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funeco.2016.07.002" title="Mutualism with aggressive wood-degrading Flavodon ambrosius (Polyporales) facilitates niche expansion and communal social structure in Ambrosiophilus ambrosia beetles." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funeco.2016.07.002" volume="23" year="2016">Kasson et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
